Another restaurant called to make reservations. Got there around 7:30 and they told us it’d be a 20 min wait. They called me an hour and a half later only to tell me they could not accommodate me; by this time of course we had already been eating elsewhere. I would comment on the food but I never go to try it. Never going there again.

Was excited to finally try this place - saw it recommended as one of Chicago's 20 Best Outdoor Restaurants (Time-out Chicago).  For those that don't know, this is a local (and popular) watering hole in Wicker Park, tucked into a mostly residential neighborhood. Great hole-in-the-wall appeal. We were fortunate coming on a Thursday (in March) just after 4:30pm. Not many customers yet at that time, we were seated right away (there were three of us). Covid protocols are good - with temp checks and required masks. The service was very friendly, from the wait staff to the manager. Inside was charming and ambiance was awesome, themed out in Mardi Gras with hanging beads, glitter masks, and lights!  The food was a bit hit or miss, though nothing was exceptional. We ordered a Shrimp Po'boy, Nashville Chicken Po'boy, and a Catfish plate with a hush puppies appetizer and beignets as the desert - with a couple of Diet Cokes for drinks. Everything just seemed like it was suffering from cost-cutting measures.  The hush puppies were deep south Cajun-style hush puppies with large pieces of peppers, onions, and corn. Despite all that mixed in, they tasted bland, dry, and somewhat stale, like they'd been sitting out or a few days old.  The french roll on the Shrimp Po'boy also tasted stale and they tried to disguise it by toasting it slightly. The shrimp seemed like it had been bought cooked and frozen, and then fried that way - it was very rubbery. It wasn't stacked with lettuce and tomato like they show in Google videos I'd previously seen. It was also dry - with not much mayo and with about an ounce of hot sauce. It didn't taste bad - and that's mostly because it didn't have much of a taste with an overall lack of seasoning.  The catfish on the other hand seemed undercooked and expired. It reminded me of fish you'd buy on sale at the supermarket because it hadn't sold in two weeks. It probably could have used another minute or two in the frying oil.  The Nashville fried chicken was good - tender on the inside and crispy on the outside with good flavor. It paired well with the Nashville Hot Sauce that was sweet and not that spicy (which we liked).  The beignets were great and easily the most authentic item we tried. Perfectly cooked, hearty and soft on the inside. Not too sweet, but a nice overall taste with the powdered sugar.  The Diet Coke was ok, tasted like it needed syrup and the fries were nothing special - just plain with some Cajun spice added. One minor quirk was the Po'boys weren't cut in thirds - didn't really make a difference, but every picture I've seen of food from here showed the Po'boys cut in thirds. Maybe their B team was duty this night, or maybe the cost-cutting is getting them through covid. Whatever the reason, it did not meet our expectations. But, not gonna write them off - perhaps it's something we'll try again in normal times.
There's literally NOTHING on the menu that wasn't delicious. Even the untraditional items like oysters. Great customer service as well!
Went there today and was extremely disappointed. Paid $19 for 1/2 dozen chargrilled oysters that were overpriced, overcooked greasy, and lacked the most important ingredient; the oyster.

Went there Saturday for some food and drinks. Had some hurricanes which were pretty tasty and went down easy. The food on the other hand was atrocious. Baked oysters were hammered and covered in cheese that was hard & chewy. I'm pretty sure the belly of the oyster was missing and it was just a shell with melted cheese. Had the sausage sliders which were over cooked and so salty. These are $6 a piece and I didn't even finish 1 of them.  Plus the food took 40 minutes to hit the table and we ordered it with the drinks.

I had a poor experience here last Friday! The General Manager was extremely rude to my family and my self. They were promoting Mardi Gras specials on their menu, which is why we decided to visit. When we got there they didn’t have Hurricanes and stated that items on their flyers are only offered to go. Then when I asked about the Jambalaya he stated that this had to be called in 24 hours in advance, however, there is no indication of this on their website or flyer. So when I mentioned that they might want to update the site, he stated “I told them to update it so, like I said I don’t develop the website”. Furthermore, as I spoke amongst my family stating that this was very misleading, the General Manager told me “It is what it is”. My aunt, shocked, asked him if this is what he said, and he replied “Yup”. I then asked if there was a number to contact for someone higher or corporate and he was very snotty and said we don’t have a corporate office, but you can go ahead and leave a review. He was very arrogant and was not pleasant at all! I wouldn’t recommend this establishment!!!!! It’s very unprofessional and it’s sad that they would allow anyone like this to manage their restaurant!

This was my fourth time at the restaurant.  The first two times were 5 star experiences.  Unfortunately the quality has declined since then.  My third visit was a take out and items were missing and there were menu discrepancies from what was shown online versus what was they actually had.  I chalked this up to a fluke and decided to give the restaurant one more try. Went back in for my fourth visit and the food was sub par at best.  The Hot Honey Chicken was over cooked and extremely dry (I've ordered this 3 times before and it used to be fantastic).  The biscuit was under cooked, flat and doughy.  I walked past the kitchen to use the wash room and saw a rack filled with the fried chicken and biscuits sitting out (restaurant had about 6 tables of people at this time) meaning that food was likely recooked in the fryer drying it out.  The fried shrimp tasted bland and not like it has in the past.  The only item from our meal that was somewhat enjoyable was the hush puppies.  Used to love this restaurant but the quality has declined over my visits that I will no longer be returning.

Fantastic. New Orleans cuisine
Good food, vibe and friendly service. Well worth visiting.
Food and atmosphere was good
The food was great! I wish they had beignets on hand tho.. I was really looking forward to those..

Zero crowd management. They had a pop up event that was obviously going to draw crowd and they allowed reservations for the very limited seating. No warning about that, which was a big disappointment. Def don’t come when it’s busy.
This place was great!  Tasty food, nice people, casual, didn't feel rushed... it checks all the boxes.  My wife Muggins ate a whole fried chicken.  She is awesome.
Different decor...good food..BEST drinks.
I dig that they have live music here. The shrimp po'boy is good and generously proportioned. Good beer and drink selection with reasonable specials.
First time gumbo was very good,service erratic
Eggplant Orleans.
Delicious
Happy hour 9-10pm. What more could you ask for?

I wanted so badly to be able to get NOLA food close to home, but I was disappointed. I felt like I was eating in Wrigleyville. The game was so loud that it was unpleasant. Took a while to get initial service and 20 minutes to get my hurricane. It was tasty, but not sweet or strong which is kind of the nature of a hurricane. The baked oysters were very good, but $3.50 each. The fried oysters were also very good. I loved their potato salad. The gumbo was the least "gumbo-like" soup I've ever been served. They put cold potato salad (cross between southern and german) in the bottom of the bowl along with the rice which not only added a very odd flavor, but drastically brought the temperature of the soup down...it was barely warm by the time we were half way done. The shrimp and andouille seemed to be thrown in at the end, almost as an after thought....their flavors were really not present in the broth. Fried chicken was $14 for 3 pcs... a small leg, wing and breast. I liked the flavor,  but my hubby hated it. There was quite a bit of "hot honey" drizzled on top which made all of the breading pretty soggy.
Authentic Southern Cuisine with a little twist,...enjoyed the food, atmosphere and the service.
Great cocktails and food. One of the best Poor Boys I've had outside of Louisiana. Chargrilled oysters were also delicious.
Great food!  Had the broiled mussels and chargrilled oysters - cooked perfectly!  Thanks!
Delicious! Great cajun flavor presentation. The brunch was fantastic and perfectly portioned. The drinks were delicious. The beignets satisfied all.
Uniquely delicious, with a great take on southern style foods, it's pricey but has an excellent staff, choice of outside/inside seating and the food is very tasty
The best fried chicken and shrimp and grits!
Great food and drink selections. Customer service is top notch. Excellent live music in a cozy environment which is located in a beautiful area of the great city of Chicago.

Absolute best gumbo I have ever had at a restaurant!! They serve it over rice and potato salad which made no sense to me but it was spectacular. The fried chicken was also incredible. It was perfectly seasoned and crispy yet moist on the inside. The atmosphere was lively and the servers were fun and friendly.

Ina Mae does Cajun fare justice.  The drinks and beer selection are on point the vibes fit well in the neighborhood.  The boils does automatically have butter on them and the kitchen was able to accommodate my pickiness.
Great atmosphere
Wow! Collard greens that put my grandmother's to shame. My wife just said she never really liked fried chicken until she tasted theirs.  Damn good food!

This food is aaammmaaazzziingggg! Me and my sister love sharing food so their family style serving was perfect! Nothing disappointed, the service was great! The atmosphere was so cozy and cool. I’ll definitely be back.

Amazing Bloody Mary with a kick! The Grand Slam really hit the spot! The gator sausage was solid (would definitely recommend), the grits were buttery, and the seasoning on the potatoes was delicious! I'll be back soon to try the gumbo!
Great drinks and attentive staff
It was a nice experience. They were out of quite a few  items on the menu: cajun elote and Zulu snowball. Our waitress was very accommodating. Overall, the food and drinks were good.
Cant wait to go back
Good food, friendly staff
Food here was pretty much amazing! Service was great too!
Loved the hot sauce. Shrimp and chicken were delicious, I bet everything is amazing.
Great food, awesome wait staff....They have a patio!!
Good Cajun food. Fun atmosphere. Get the gumbo, you won't be disappointed.

As a native New Orleanian...Who Dat!...I really wanted to like this place more than I did. In fact, finding good New Orleans food in Chicago has been more miss than hit. I’m glad Ina Mae’s exists in case of an “I need a poboy” emergency, but for now it’s a great place to grab a drink, and I’m glad you can now get the gumbo without potato salad on the bottom....this is NEVER or should be a thing.
Love the po'boy sandwiches

This is my 3rd time here, the staff is routinely unfriendly (aside from hostess). They’re a New Orleans joint that blatantly advertises this fact, with boozy slushies. However I have yet to have one. They’re slushee machine has been broken all 3 times.
Very nice atmosphere and staff. The music was live and great! The food is very good and the portions are generous. Nice neighborhood but parking is tight.
Wonderful music and very nice alternatives for late dining

My family and I just had father's day brunch here. What a great experience. Great food, service and ambiance for kids & adults alike. Huge compliments to the GM Garrett. He was busting his butt to make sure everyone at the restaurant had an amazing experience. I haven't seen anyone work that hard to make other people happy at a restaurant maybe ever. Really well done Garrett and Ina Mae! Thank you!
The food was delicious 😍
Slow service.

You do not want to overlook this place for amazing quick bites or real meals right off Milwaukee in wicker park. Whatever you get make sure you order the biscuit -comes with house made pepper jelly- so simple and good. Can also vouch for the Mac and cheese. Check this place out.
Love this place!
Delicious, huge portions, southern comfort. The slushies and sno cones are perfect for the summer.
Went for the fried Chicken and bingo!
Friendly service and great food. Loved the blackened cauliflower and fried chicken! It can get a little loud when they are busy, but it's to be expected with the more bar type atmosphere.
This is my kind of place. Super relaxed. Incredibly friendly, accommodating staff. Out of this world food.
The food was excellent the experience was great so where servers I will travel across the city just to go there again
I can't say enough good things about the service and the food in this place. I have recommended it to everyone I know. It was the best southern food I have had since being in Louisiana.

Waited 35 min for our reservation. Normally that's understandable but our order was incomplete. Missed the gumbo bowl completely, asked twice, got a cup...  aand got the wrong chicken dish. Not sure how common that is but was a bummer as the food was good and authentic. They were out of biegnets which is a shame since we were seated late. Really should get their act together, would absolutely not recommended.

I’ve been twice.  Wondering if anyone experience this.... First experience... Order four items. 2 come out, then 1, and finally the other. Most people like to eat all at once. Excuse.. something about the kitchen staff  Second experience.... Mouth ready for chicken and waffles for brunch. No waffles... Excuse... something is wrong with the waffle maker  Mom orders some brunch combo at the top of the menu. Something breakfast item they ran out of substitution...a garden salad. Please tell me how a garden salad goes with grits and sausage. I’m still laughing.  Food good. Service questionable for that price.

Drinks are good, but I haven't had anything that really had amazed me. I do however love the atmosphere, which is a new Orleans themed vibe. I have not yet eaten any food here yet, so this is based solely on drinks and atmosphere.
Fantastic Sunday brunch. The hot sausage was amazing. Definitely worth checking out.
Enjoyed the fried shrimp po'boy & yummy biscuit.
OMG! The food here is freakin delicious. All I can say is go check this place out, you won’t be disappointed.
Gem in Wicker Park!  Not what I was expecting from the outside. Great food and an extended happy hour selection. Will definitely recommend!
Amazing food, amazing drinks, great place to chill with friends and family

Good location for New Orleans based cuisine. Their gumbo and street corn with crawfish are tasty.  Seating is slightly tight and mostly high chairs/bar stools.  They also have bingo nights and other activities for diners depending on the day of the week, check their website online to plan better. Get a reservation before hand, it’s worth it.
The food was good
A lil expensive but it is in Wicker, friendly staff and fun events make it worth your while
Dinner menu ... food too salty ... portions too small ... where is the meat? ... almost missed it ... very little meat ... very large bill.
The food was everything I expected and more!
Great brunch menu.  I do have to agree with some of the other reviewers that the food was a bit too salty.  Especially the fried stuff.  But the biscuits and gravy were solid.
I heard about this place from a friend but I am not a fan of the food. The sandwich was very salty and it was replaced with chicken. I did not care for the taste.
Good New Orleans food and wonderful music.
Service wasn’t great very inattentive and rude. Food was over salted. Serving of potato salad was laughable. See pic attached
(Translated by Google) Oh, yes.  (Original) Oh ya.
If you crave some southern comfort food, this is it. =) Love their grits and that chicken and waffles is bomb yo!
Great seafood and drinks.

Our son took us here for Sunday brunch just last weekend. Very good Louisiana cooking. You don’t have to go to New Orleans to eat a great tasting shrimp and grits . We started with beignets😋. And each one of us ordered different kinds of entree, Gumbo, chicken and waffles, Louisiana grand slam , crawfish scrambled eggs, All are so yummy 🤤. And we even bought 2 bottles of their “hot FA sauce “ to go. Great customer service, great selections of drinks. A multicultural environment , everyone is welcome. Bring your family, your friends and enjoy.
Nice place.  Some interesting cocktails.  (One has peanuts in it!)  I think the food's a little overpriced, with the exception of the happy hour fried chicken special.
Enjoyed brunch! Chicken and Waffjes were to die for! Very nice service.  Melinda was very personable.
Great food and drinks! I thought I left Chicago and was having dinner in New Orleans!

Food was a bit salty for my taste. Eggplant Orleans was tasty. Wait staff was very attentive. No care taken to clean plates/bowls along the sides when serving gumbo or packing up containers to go. That was a turn off
Strong, but incredibly tasty drinks!

Went for my husband's birthday tonight. The food was so good. We had the elotes, which was served cold like a salad and kind of threw me off, but once I added the lime it was good. The biscuits and hush puppies are amazing. Catfish- YES. Shrimp were really good. Oh and so was the mac. Basically it was delicious and our server was really cool too.
Nice fried shrimp po' boy! Cheap wine on tap!
Replacing the Beachwood Inn with this pseudo blue collar aesthetic is a crime.
Good sandwiches

I just went to Ina Mae’s and I have officially died and gone to food heaven. The chicken and waffles were absolutely delicious. I also ate the biscuits, alligator sausage, and grits were scrumptious. None of the food is average here, everything is far above typical trendy restaurant. The staff was also very friendly and the food came out quickly. Can’t wait to come back for dinner and the Wednesday night ‘Peel and Eat Shrimp’ 😋😋😋😋😋

Service was great. The chicken and waffles were drool worthy. There was construction going on during my visit making the task of finding free parking terrible. Once inside I was taken aback by the charm of the space. The manager allowed my guest and I to view their cellar (which just holds equipment) and loft space upstairs. They were in the middle of remodeling the upstairs space as a possible AirBnB location. I'd definitely loved to stay there.
Cocktails and Cajun!
We tried several dishes, and they were  all delicious.
Great food, everything on the menu is delicious! Kudos to Chef Brian!
Amazing fried seafood tower, great fried chicken, dirty rice good, service amazing. Burger, terrible. Will still be back over and over.
Get the seafood mac and cheese. Immediately.
Amazing friend chicken! Go for their happy hour specials

Went here for a Scotch Educational seminar and learned a lot about Scotch, but discovered Ina Mae Tavern!  We had the Arugula salad with pickled melon and char grilled oysters.  The salad was very good and refreshing.  The oysters were topped with a cheesy sauce and were very tasty.  This is the perfect place to enjoy a drink and New Orleans style food.  We want to come back here for the Po' Man's Seafood Tower (Shrimp, oysters, catfish, hush puppies, and crispy potatoes sounds like like a bargain at $36 for 2 or 3 people.
Everything was delicious!! Definitely coming back for more!

Delicious brunch food! I had the Crawfish scramble eggs and it was great. The vignette with their coffee was also a perfect end. Highly recommend this Louisiana inspired spot for it's chill atmosphere and quality food - if you like seafood you'll love the options here!

Really good Southern cooking! Very good service! Delicious eggplant appetizer, wonderful chargrilled oysters, great crispy fried chicken with biscuits, po-boy sandwiches on crispy, light French bread, heartwarming gumbo! Can't wait to go back!

The food here is great. I've done couples dinner, big group brunch, and small group lunch. I can't speak to their authenticity but it sure tastes delicious. The seafood platters are perfect for groups, the poboys are giant, and the chicken and waffles will make anyone's head turn. Ina Mae has the food figured out but their service needs fine tuning. Multiple servers/staff required just to greet, sit, order drinks, order food, and pay the bill. Felt disorganized each time I went but the food has me returning.
Great food, staff was awesome.
Delicious southern fare. Great atmosphere and friendly staff.

Had an amazing experience there last weekend at Brunch. The servers were very accommodating with our request to switch tables, and the food was delicious too.The seafood tower was flavourful and fried to perfection, shrimp and grits was tasty, and the butter on the chicken and waffles was edible on its own. Will definitely head there again with friends.
Love this place! Especially the fish platter; light meal for four and fills up two easily! Good beer selection too.

Grew up in the neighborhood, seen this place evolve into to Ina Mae’s Tavern, read the article on the owners concept and was super excited to check this place out. Finally got chance to check it out during a restaurant crawl. Let me tell you when people do crawls this is the a great opportunity for you to expose yourself to new people. They failed. I waited almost 45 for the 3 item smaller pictured below. Restaurant wasn’t that busy and numerous people that arrived after me got served first. Food was just ok.  Definitely not worth the wait. Probably won’t go back. Great concept though. Decor is cool.
Very comfortable and great staff
Fantastic

Adorable space, lovely service, but horrible food! We ordered the seafood tower which is a mixture of fried seafood things and they were so salty the food was rendered inedible. Po boys had the same problem, way too much salt in the batter food was inedible. Seafood mac and cheese was probably the best thing we ate, but it was not anything special. Super disappointed because everything else about the space, service and drinks were great.
Food was decent; service was slow and poor (they were not busy). We're glad we tried it but probably won't return.
I came here for dinner and a drink. The hush puppies were delicious! Everything we ordered was very good and prices were reasonable. I will definitely go back.
Food is awesome and they serve Spiteful Lager.
Food was delicious
Great service! Good beers and a nice little selection of seafood nibbles.
Excellent drinks and food!  I'll be back!
The food is amazing, the atmosphere is great. And The Chicken.. !!!!!
The seafood mac & cheese is unbelievable.  Super cool atmosphere, as well
Love it

Beignets are tasty and big. With that said, menu items are small and pricey. And that is mostly due to their a la carte style menu. I wouldn't say they encourage family style ordering for the table style dining, but that is what you should do if you want to maximize your experience here. Bring friends. The catfish was well seasoned, the draft selection reasonably varied, but the house-made hot sauces were forgettable vinegar solutions. Expect this place to always be out of crawfish for about half the year as they do not use the frozen variety when the fresh are out of season. You'll probably get a better creole experience nearby at Fifolet, but If you are into NOLA, and need more cajun-esque food in your life, experience this while you can because I don't expect it to be around for very long...

Ina Mae’s is, unfortunately, a spot that seems to have a bit more style than substance. The decor, food menu, and cocktail selections all wonderfully establish Ina Mae’s Louisiana vibe. Sadly, the service and the quality of the food can’t quite live up to the same high bar as the atmosphere. My girlfriend and I were attended to infrequently by the wait staff, and while the food was decent (we had the alligator Po Boy, the Cajun Elote, and the Fried Chicken), it was nothing worth coming back for. Overall, Ina Mae’s is a firmly middle-of-the-road establishment that pulls you in with its Cajun veneer, but fails to make you yearn for more
BBQ Shrimp all good
Six of us thouroughly enjoyed the brunch. We frequently visit NOLA. Great to have a place in Chicago that rivals the great local spots there!
Service was very friendly. However, food was ok

Such a unique experience in the city! We got the ‘seafood tower’ and while we were not expecting it to be completely fried, we weren’t mad about it! They have reasonable prices on both drink and food and they have a great variety of options to try that I have not seen anywhere else in the city! I am excited to go back and try something different! One very small suggestion is putting hooks under tall tables (which were about half of them) so that ladies have a place to hang their purse!

Read the Trib feature on Ina’s and had me after 2 words; Beignets and Seafood....got two orders of beignets to go and they are piece of heaven.  Had a delicious cocktail while I waited...friendly professional staff...highly recommend

They are still working to get the kinks out as they are fairly new. I went there recently and the drinks we're well done and inventive. The food was especially tasty. I appreciate the range of vegan to meat loving options. Try the hush puppies if you go. I did have a problem with my order that they worked to make it right. I'm looking forward to returning once they tighten up their operation.
Great servers. Food was a little overpriced, but probably normal for the neighborhood.

The two cocktails I had were fantastic. The La Louisianne and a rum based one that I forgot the name of both were excellent. The food was fine. The elotes were nice and fresh, but no real wow factor. I split an order of the seafood tower with a friend and it was a pile of fried seafood. I didn't feel anything was very flavorful and it felt like standard street fest fare.

I have been waiting for a true cajun spot in the neighborhood. This is as good as it gets. That gumbo though! Brought back memories of my grandmother. I actually clapped out loud in the middle of the restaurant after I ate it. Well done.
Good drinks, good atmosphere.  But for the love of God - lose the stadium country music.

Came here on opening day, it seems like the kind of place where you order a bunch of dishes to share and they just bring it out to you whenever any part of your order is ready. I got a Po boy, which was just okay. My friends seemed to enjoy the Crawfish and shrimp but said the portions we're a bit small. It seemed the people bringing out our food were kinda confused about who ordered what since we very frequently almost got offered someones else's dish when it was for a different table. I would come back sometime again on a little less busy day to give it another shot.
Great start even on day 1.  Amazing chicken, biscuit, sauces, and service.
